What machine I use. It’s the most popular question in my comments.
My main machine is @everlastwelders PowerTIG 325EXT.
More then enough power - 325 amps. Stable Arc. AC/DC. Universal machine for everything I need at the shop. Mine is also has the watercooled torch and water cooler. Best set up for welding aluminum.
The machine has 4 waves types for welding aluminum - triangular, sine, soft square and advanced square.
I use pedal for control amperage in process (have no idea how much amps I run for different materials and  thickness, pedal control is the best control).
Let’s talk about thin materials:
5amps is the lowest start for DC mode.
10amps for AC mode.
It makes work with very thin materials super easy, no burns through. Also the machine has pulse set up for both mods AC and DC.
I mean what else do you need? It has literally everything for easy TIG welding at any shop.
Use link in bio for order your green monster. With my link you will get free upgrade to NOVA kit - 25’ long torch (torch type depends on set up you purchase) and 25’ long pedal.
I work with @everlastwelders for more than 5 years and not going to even think to switch to another brand. Great quality and the best price on the market.
#weldmeanweldgreen

Heat management.
Look at those absolutely flat in line outlets (tail tips) on the exhaust system. It looks even better after I welded them to Double X-pipe. It’s very important to know how distortion works and how and where the parts are going to move in process. You can manage it with right starting spot and direction of your weld. It works for manual and positioner welding. Want to learn more about this topic? Subscribe to exclusive content. I’m going to talk in detail about heat management.

Why I recommend do as much welding as possible on positioner.
1. Less distortion. Especially important for Stainless Steel.
2. Parts shrink less when you weld each connection in one pass. 
3. Less heat input.
4. Takes less time than manual welding and helps to increase labor productivity.
Follow for more.
